  "text": "In multiple testing, we aim to separate the non-null cases from null cases. A testing procedure can be represented by a binary rule δ δ δ = (δ1, · · · , δn) ∈ {0, 1} n , where δi = 0/1 indicates that we claim that case i is null/non-null. Multiple testing is a compound decision problem [CITATION_1] ) since all tests are combined and evaluated together. The development of a multiple testing procedure involves two steps: (i) deriving a test statistic Ti that ranks hypotheses from the most significant to the least significant, and (ii) setting a cutoff t for Ti to control the FDR at α. This leads to a thresholding rule:",
